day 7 journal / poem

today i remembered 
holding my face and going oh my god oh my god
totally consumed by the most tender,
liquid mix of joy and grief.
simultaneously and wholly,
holy gift of a breaking heart
joy
and grief
like two colors twisting and embracing on a canvas
except the canvas has no end
and there is no place the color hasn’t touched
and nowhere the colors haven’t mixed.
perfect joy, perfect grief
knowing suddenly
knowing suddenly
that all there is to know in this life
all there ever is to do
is love
and all there is to love in this world
someday must die and disappear.
what a bittersweet thing
to be a friend
to be an artist
to be a mother
to be Creator
and know the beautiful pain
of loving.

day 11 journal entry

today i witnessed something that fascinated me:
i noticed a thought that had been lingering in my head.
this notion kept pulling my focus,
but for hours maybe days i hadn’t ever given it my full attention—
given it the mic, the stage
to be heard, to be seen.
i wouldn’t really look at it,
and it didn’t go anywhere.
it just sat there and took up space,
and i let it.
like a guest who wouldn’t take a hint, whom i refused to address.

meanwhile as i turned my attention to other things,
i had trouble relaxing.
i confided in (complained to) my friends about my anxiety
i condescended to myself for my brain fog.
why can’t you just be ‘on’ ?
why aren’t you killing it ?
maybe you should give up and skip today.
and i judged myself for that too.

and then, because i’m committed to journaling every day this year,
i sat down to write.
and when that notion came up this time,
i looked right at it.  i gave it space.
i let it speak.
listening patiently, writing it all down,
i let it say everything it had to say.
i even asked it some questions and let it say some more.
and when it had finally said its piece,
suddenly it was… free.

i watched as this thought
literally lifted off and left my consciousness
leaving room
tangible, even physical space
there, in my being.
and eventually, in its absence, 
another thought slowly arose
stepping forward into the light.
a much kinder thought
an expansive one
an exciting one.
and i wrote a journal entry;
i wrote a song.

i sense that thoughts and feelings, much like people
often just want to be heard and seen
lovingly acknowledged.
it is said, ‘what one resists persists.’ instead, when i commit my presence and undivided attention to the moment, it actually creates freedom and flow.  what magic lies waiting behind that which i reject, suppress, or ignore??

day 35 rebirthday

today is my dad’s rebirthday.  he died six years ago today after a fourteen-year journey with Alzheimer’s disease.  every year on his rebirthday i choose a quality of his that i decide to embody for the year.  this year i choose: 

*spontaneity*

last night when i pulled the car over in the middle of nowhere and ran out into the snow under the stars, i was reminded of him, his verve for life, his natural ability to create fun just about anywhere.  he was a romantic man, too, and there was a feeling in the air that made me long to share adventures like this with my future beloved.

this year i’m tuning into the little moments in between which, with just a little willingness to improvise, could spark into something great.

i love you forever Big Joey P
Mom and i miss ya 💜

day 44 journal entry

as long as i’m alive,
i’m living.
how easy to forget
that this life is a gift, giving
one waking, living gift being given in real time
a gift so complex and rich, simple and pure
that can be received in every moment
and in every moment in between every moment.
do you get that Nicholas?
your life is a gift that is being given to you *constantly*.
to receive it is an action in & of itself-
it takes presence.
v i g i l a n c e.
so like, be here now
and now
and now
because it’s all being handed right to you.
all you ever need to do 
all you ever get to do
is show up.
show up with your palms up and open
show up with your eyes awake.
show up ready and listening
with your ears
with your touch
with your senses.
feel what is here to feel.
here is all there ever is.
now is all there ever is.
are you getting this?
are you paying attention?
or are you worried about the way you said that one thing
are you worried about what might happen Friday or next year
when you fill your moment with what might have been
or what might be
what are you missing that is right here?
you got this.
stay present.
stay in it.
and don’t give so many fucks about the imperfections.
‘imperfections’
what do you call ‘imperfections’ in a piece of great art?
you don’t, it’s just art.
and more often than not that’s what you like about it.
like that section in Voodoo Child (Slight Return)
when Jimi falls out of time w the band.
they just stay in it,
until it returns to equilibrium.
and it’s your favorite part of the song.
so thank you Mind
you can take a seat in the back.
your opinion will be requested when it is needed.
your comments will be heard.
meantime, take a breather.
i’m behind the wheel.

part one:

the people saved WALK THE MOON. 

by Christmas 2009, our lineup of band members had gone thru several incarnations already.
the latest members (dear college friends, with whom i wrote the first versions of songs like Anna Sun) had just gone their separate ways for separate reasons.  before they’d left, we’d had a hard conversation.  they helped me to see i’d been avoiding my family situation.  Dad’s Alzheimer’s was getting worse, and i needed to accept that and step up as the man in the family.  support my mother and help take care of my father.  their words were wisdom, tough love.  they were good friends.

and now they were gone.

i strongly considered calling it quits.  it had already been four-and-a-half years of playing as many shows as we could during summer breaks and on weekends at college.  band battles, bar gigs, busking outside the aquarium.  we’d built a little following… some kids in Cincinnati, students at colleges around Ohio + Indiana, whoever else had found us on Myspace… still, we were nobody.  every gig had been a hustle.  we definitely weren’t making any money.  and now i had no bandmates.

by all logic WALK THE MOON should have died that Christmas.  instead, something possessed me to hold on.  a sort of deranged certainty took over me.  i decided my band was gonna get signed and blow up.  i just knew it would happen, eventually.  play enough gigs, collect enough emails, hand out enough burned CDs, and it was inevitable.  just a matter of time.

and so, with a defiant, reckless, quirky fervor, i began making my comeback.
pretending to be a band manager, i booked a dozen gigs at venues who were expecting a rock band.  of course, i had no band members, but the venues didn’t know that.  what i did have was songs.  i figured, if i had songs, whoever could learn to play them could be in WALK THE MOON for the night.  so i started going to see other bands in town… i’d catch a show on Wednesday, see a guitar player i liked enough, go up to him after the show, and ask him if he wanted play in my show on Saturday.  it was madness like this for about a year.  if you came to a WALK THE MOON show in 2010... (cont'd in comments)

< i want! i want! > pt. ii

an ancient, derelict downtown warehouse.  huge paper canvases duct-taped to the walls, painted wildly by countless anonymous hands.  tree sculptures and “i want! i want!” written all around.  everywhere you looked, a painted face.  five hundred Cincinnati kids who climbed the winding staircase, ducked through the brick archway, and packed themselves into the who-knows-what-it-used-to-be chamber to catch some local live music and see what this band WALK THE MOON was all about.  our album release party at the Mockbee in downtown Cincinnati, Ohio was a huge undertaking — all of the beautiful people who volunteered their time for the music video (also filmed at the Mockbee) we invited back for the release, and many of them helped us recreate the atmosphere of the video so the attendees could spend their evening hanging out in another dimension, in our universe.  even Pones Inc., the dance team from the video, came onstage and into the crowd for a flashmob during our cover of “Thriller”. we finished our set and requested everyone turn towards the back of the room and sit down so we could all see what was projected on the wall.  and i remember feeling this untamable electricity of emotion in my chest as the world saw “Anna Sun” for the first time…

-@nicholaspetricholas
 
big big love to the people who were critical to the Anna Sun music video taking flight, including but not limited to: Patrick Meier (director), Kim Popa (choreographer), Pones Inc. (dance troupe), Katie Grace Carlson, Tim Hein, & all of the volunteers who donated their time + energy!

“Anna Sun”, strangely, began as an attempt to recreate “Once In A Lifetime” by Talking Heads.  if you squint really hard, you may notice the repeating call-and-response choruses “what do you know” and “letting the days go by” vaguely mirror each other.  however, as it has always happened for me, whenever i start with some really specific source material, my song ends up taking me somewhere else entirely.  whatever David Byrne was feeling when he was writing Remain In Light, i don’t know, but when i was sat in the dark in my parent’s basement in June 2009 with a pen in my hand, my heart was in mourning.  i felt like i had tripped and fallen off a cliff, tumbling from the happiest time in my life into this strange lonely free-fall.  college was over, summertime was here, and the rest of my life seemed to be waiting, arms folded, foot tapping.  this particular afternoon, a month or so after graduation, my ex-girlfriend texted me hat she’d visited the empty campus and how strange it was.  that she and her friends set off fireworks in the South Quad, and that they… “rattled this ghost town”. i remember being shocked by that description and struck with a craving to be alone with my journal.  i went to the basement and left the lights off, so the only light was the evening sun peeking thru the shades, and I started writing: “screen falling off the door, door hanging off the hinges…” one of WALK THE MOON's last gigs during the schoolyear had taken place at a neighboring central-Ohio college, playing a party for the seniors at the town pub (these little Ohio college towns often had just one pub). the pub's entrance was a screen door that was barely attached to its frame, and that night when the class of 2009 raged their last rage, it felt like the building might crumble to rubble.  this and a thousand other college and childhood memories supercut through my head and began infusing themselves into song... (cont'd in comments)

Part two of the secret world of song camps looks at the different roles in a songwriting session. There are producers who sit behind a console desk or computer and record, arrange and craft the instrumental and track the vocal. Often they double as engineers who use their technical knowledge to select mics, set up signal chains, and ensure the best recording. Then there is the topliner, a singer who generates melodies on the fly, throwing ideas at the instrumental, looking for the best hooks. Often the top liner is also a songwriter who crafts chords and lyrics to fit the topline melody. And then there is of course the artist who performs the piece. 

These roles aren’t always clearly divided - most musicians have multiple skills. But for the sake of understanding how each role is essential to creating a song, we asked four musical luminaries to embody one of these roles and break it down: producer/engineer Alex Tumay, topliner Wolftyla, Songwriter and Walk the Moon frontman Nicholas Petricca and Artist Grace VanderWall.

This conversation happened live at the College of Performing Arts at The New School as part of Anti Social Camp 2023, the largest song camp in the world that is working to revive to the NYC songwriting scene. 

Available on Spotify, Apple Podcasts and anywhere you get podcasts

< TALKING IS HARD > pt. iii

It’s hard to put the TALKING IS HARD era into words. It was a magical time that saw dream after dream come to fruition. It took us to stages we’d longed to play. Coast to coast, nation to nation. At one point, we played twenty two countries in just over a month. We were putting in the work, watching our dreams come true, and having a hell of a time along the way. 

A two year blur of ever-expanding venues and festivals, early morning flights and radio performances, new experiences and the ache of missing home. It was a huge rush. One massive hustle-hustle-go-go-go. But every day was worth it when we ended up on stage in a room with you all, the listeners.  We’ve said it a million times, but our show is the heart of the WALK THE MOON universe. The band/fan connection. And that’s the thing I remember most about this time. The feeling of being on stage with my friends, connecting with the world through songs we’d crafted in that Masonic lodge in northern Kentucky. 

- @brosemaiman

unpacking this experience in layers…

the waves of anticipation, discomfort, excitement leading up to this peaceful moment.  my supplies packed in a bin and a couple suitcases; the noisy, bumpy ride north in an RV; the feeling of leaving home, of being on the way somewhere, of approaching arrival…  i feel equally like i’m headed into total unknown, high adventure, off the map, and equally like i’m coming home.  my sixth Burn.  each time, this place feels deeply familiar, like i might have lived many lifetimes here, and yet each time, there is a profound presence of mystery — you just never know what’s going to happen.

pictured: a blissful bikeride, fully dropped in, soaring across the open playa and into town.  the noisy quiet, vast space, hot sun, and this strange, welcoming, temporary city.

< what if nothing > pt. i

our third record < what if nothing > came from an exploration of extremes: the yin-yang, the light and the dark, life and death, the full spectrum.  listening back, it feels like a surreal representation of what i was experiencing in my personal life. 

Summer 2016 was a mysterious portal for me.  some difficult lows would lead to profound moments of growth, freedom, and inspiration for the album.  i had cancelled our summer tour because i couldn’t bare going out on the road again while my dad was so sick.  my girlfriend and i, after almost five years, had decided to break up.  and i had moved back home to Cincinnati to be close to family.  maybe it was the spaciousness of being back in Ohio, or the confronting proximity of my father’s illness; whatever the reason, i received a strong call to venture deeper with myself.  i got my own music studio space downtown.  i studied Kung Fu, Tarot, and Kundalini Yoga.  i sat in ceremony with indigenous medicine.  i spent a week in the desert at a strange gathering called Burning Man.  and i spent a lot of time with my mom visiting my dad at his care facility. 

by the time i reunited with the band that fall & winter to put together the next record, i felt like i was becoming a different person.  the sorrow of losing my dad and the grace i was experiencing in my spiritual practices and adventures were transforming me into a more whole human being.  i felt somehow connected to more of the world, to everyone who had ever experienced profound loss.  my lyrics, even my voice began to feel different.  songs like “Surrender”, “Kamikaze”, and “Sound Of Awakening” were coming through that i never would have been able to write or sing before.  it didn’t matter what the song was about — i found i could access my pain or joy and bring it into the music, into the light; and each time, it felt like a gift from my dad. (cont’d in comments)

< HEIGHTS > pt. ii:  as i write this post i’m filled with gratitude for the art that we have gotten to make as a band. < HEIGHTS > is my favorite record we’ve ever made, with my favorite music videos. (besides you, Anna Sun, you’ll always be the Queen)

“Can You Handle My Love??” — a strange prance through our collective subconscious.  a dreamlike non-sequitur sequence for a song that confesses my hopelessly flawed humanity.  i love the moments of pure personality that come thru in the big white performance space, like the very last shot when we all scatter in different directions, totally unplanned.  the original cut of the video did not even have this performance setup; we added it last minute and it became the soul of the thing.

“Fire In Your House” — another confessional tune which calls out that master saboteur who i imagine lives in all of us.  our director Nina Kramer came to us with an inspired concept, beautiful and simple, with depth for us to make it our own.  it would include a tribute to the great South African artist and activist Johnny Clegg, my friend and hero who wrote the song with me and his son, Jesse, and who died tragically in 2019.  in addition to the montage of Johnny himself, the visual style of the scenes in the “house”, which mixes color with black&white, is a reference to the 1988 music video for his song “I Call Your Name”. on set, for awhile i was distraught and confused about how to play my character in those scenes, until i realized “…OH.  i AM the Devil.” muahaha
i particularly love watching Sean and Eli bust up the set with baseball bats.  and i loved having such a huge space to express myself through dance.
this video features three additional members:  Lachlan West who tours with us, Paul Meany formerly of Mutemath who produced the song, and Jesse Clegg. 
i'll say it:  probably my favorite piece of art we’ve ever made.
-@nicholaspetricholas
